Thought: I have verified both the behavior and the solution. I can now provide the final explanation.
<code>
final_answer("In C++, if you declare a variable and don't assign a value to it, the value of that variable is undefined. It's not guaranteed to be 0 or any other specific value, it's just some indeterminate value. It is known as garbage value, which means that whatever value was already in that memory location will remain there until assigned a new value.

However, there's an exception when this variable is a global one (outside any functions), a static local variable, or a member of a class or struct. In these cases, these uninitialized variables are automatically initialized to zero.

What you're seeing might be due to your specific compiler setup. Some compilers will automatically initialize variables to 0 in debug builds, but not in release builds. This is done as a safety measure, to avoid undefined behavior causing crashes or security vulnerabilities.

About the second part of your question, to initialize every element in an array to 1 without using a loop, you can use std::array or std::vector and fill them using fill() function:

```cpp
#include <array>
#include <algorithm> 

int main()
{
  std::array<int,5> arr;
  std::fill(arr.begin(), arr.end(), 1);
}
```

This will make every element of array equal to 1. Note that although you’re not used a loop explicitly, internally fill will use one to do the assignment.")
